'''Ben Gannon-Doak''' (born '''Ben Doak''', 11 November 2005) is a Scottish [[professional footballer]] who plays as a [[Midfielder|right winger]] or attacking [[midfielder]] for [[Premier League]] club [[AFC Bournemouth|Bournemouth]] and the [[Scotland national football team|Scotland national team]].

He began his youth career with local side Dalry Rovers before joining [[Ayr United F.C.|Ayr United]] and later [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]]; making his senior debut for the latter in January 2022. Shortly thereafter, he signed for [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]], where he became the youngest Scottish player to appear in the [[Premier League]]. In 2024, he spent a season on loan at [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]], earning EFL Young Player of the Month in November. In August 2025, he transferred to Bournemouth for an initial £20 million. Internationally, he has represented Scotland at under-16, under-17 and [[Scotland national under-21 football team|under-21]] level, and made his senior debut against [[Poland national football team|Poland]] in September 2024.

== Early life ==
Ben Gannon-Doak (né Ben Doak)<ref>{{cite web |author=<!-- not stated --> |date= |title=Birth registers |url=https://www.scotlandspeople.gov.uk |website=Scotland's People |location=Edinburgh, Scotland |publisher= |access-date=26 March 2026}}</ref> was born in the small town of [[Dalry, North Ayrshire|Dalry]], [[Ayrshire]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ardrossanherald.com/news/19583355.garnock-valley-friends-united-17-scotland-squad/|title=Garnock Valley: Friends are united for Under 17 Scotland squad|publisher=Adrossan & Saltcoats Herald|date=21 September 2021|accessdate=29 January 2022}}</ref> on 11 November 2005.<ref name="PremProfile">{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/en/players/496208/ben-doak/overview |title=Ben Doak: Overview |publisher=Premier League |access-date=4 July 2025 }}</ref>

== Club career ==
Gannon-Doak began his career at hometown club Dalry Rovers, before moving to [[Ayr United F.C.|Ayr United]] and then onto [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ardrossanherald.com/news/19917010.ben-doak-former-dalry-rovers-footballer-makes-debut-celtic/|title=Ben Doak: Former Dalry Rovers footballer makes debut for Celtic|publisher=Adrossan & Saltcoats Herald|date=12 February 2022|accessdate=3 April 2022}}</ref>

=== Celtic ===
On 26 December 2021, having turned 16 the previous month, Gannon-Doak was named on the bench for Celtic's 3–1 win away to [[St Johnstone F.C.|St Johnstone]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/59715615|title=St Johnstone 1–3 Celtic|publisher=BBC Sport|date=26 December 2021|accessdate=29 January 2022}}</ref> On 29 January 2022, he made his Celtic debut, coming on as a 68th minute substitute in a 1–0 [[Scottish Premiership]] win against [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/60093484|title=Celtic 1–0 Dundee United|publisher=BBC Sport|date=29 January 2022|accessdate=29 January 2022}}</ref>

=== Liverpool ===
Gannon-Doak signed with [[Premier League]] club [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] in March 2022, with Celtic due to receive training compensation of around £600,000.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://talksport.com/football/1076780/liverpool-beat-leeds-signing-of-celtic-teenager-ben-doak-transfer-news/ |title=KOP CAPTURE Liverpool beat Leeds to signing of 16-year-old Celtic starlet Ben Doak for compensation fee of around £600,000 |first=Sam |last=May |publisher=Talksport |date=31 March 2022 |accessdate=3 April 2022}}</ref> On 9 November 2022, he made his debut for Liverpool when he came on as a 74th minute substitute in a 3–2 penalty shoot-out win against [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] in the third round of the [[2022–23 EFL Cup]] at [[Anfield]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.theguardian.com/football/2022/nov/09/liverpool-derby-county-carabao-cup-match-report|title=Kelleher's shootout saves see Liverpool scrape past Derby in Carabao Cup|date=9 November 2022|work=The Guardian|accessdate=10 November 2022}}</ref> Five days later, he signed his first professional contract with Liverpool, having reached the age of 17.<ref>{{cite news |title=Liverpool hand Ben Doak his first professional contract – five days after debut aged 16 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/63626345| date=14 November 2022|access-date=14 November 2022 |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.stv.tv/sport/scotland-under-21-star-ben-doak-signs-first-professional-contract-with-liverpool |title=Scotland under-21 star Ben Doak signs first pro deal with Liverpool |first=Peter |last=Cassidy |website=STV Sport |date=14 November 2022 |accessdate=14 November 2022}}</ref> He made his league debut for Liverpool on 26 December in a 3–1 win at [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]], becoming the youngest Scottish player to appear in the Premier League.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/64098845 |title=Stefan Bajcetic: The 'cheeky' teenager and his 'Christmas story' |publisher=BBC Sport |date=26 December 2022 |accessdate=27 December 2022 |first=Harry |last=Poole}}</ref>

On 30 July 2023, Gannon-Doak scored his first senior goal for Liverpool in a pre-season friendly match against [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]], with his side winning 4–0 at the [[National Stadium, Singapore|Singapore National Stadium]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=31 July 2023 |title='It's a great feeling' – Bobby Clark and Ben Doak react to first senior goals – Liverpool FC |url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/its-great-feeling-bobby-clark-and-ben-doak-react-first-senior-goals |access-date=7 August 2023 |publisher=Liverpool F.C. |language=en}}</ref> In December 2023, he was longlisted for the [[BBC Young Sports Personality of the Year Award]].<ref>{{cite web |title=BBC Young Sports Personality of the Year 2023 top three revealed |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/2023/bbc-young-sports-personality-of-the-year-2023-top-3 |publisher=BBC Media Centre |access-date=4 December 2023 |date=1 December 2023}}</ref> He missed most of the 2023–24 season after he underwent knee surgery in December.<ref name = different/>

==== Loan to Middlesbrough ====
On 30 August 2024, Gannon-Doak joined [[EFL Championship]] side [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] on a season-long loan.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2024-08-30 |title=Middlesbrough sign Ben Doak from Liverpool on season-long loan |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/cy4lwjwmjlvo |access-date=2024-08-30 |publisher=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> On 28 September, he made his first start for the club and scored his first competitive senior career goal in a 2–0 win over [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2024-09-28 |title=WATCH: Liverpool winger just scored his FIRST EVER club goal |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/watch-liverpool-winger-just-scored-150500326.html |access-date=2024-10-10 |publisher=Yahoo Sports |language=en-GB}}</ref>

After registering five assists in as many games in November 2024 he won the [[EFL Young Player of the Month]] award.<ref name="Nov24 YPOTM">{{Cite web |title=Ben Doak wins EFL Young Player of the Month award – Liverpool FC |url=https://www.liverpoolfc.com/news/ben-doak-wins-efl-young-player-month-award?amp=1 |access-date=2025-01-02 |website=www.liverpoolfc.com}}</ref>

===Bournemouth===
On 18 August 2025, Gannon-Doak signed for fellow Premier League side [[AFC Bournemouth|Bournemouth]] for an initial fee of £20m with a further £5m in add-ons.<ref>{{cite web |author=<!-- not stated --> |date=18 August 2025 |title=Ben Gannon Doak transfer news: Bournemouth sign winger from Liverpool in a deal worth up to £25m |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11669/13414118/ben-gannon-doak-transfer-news-bournemouth-sign-winger-from-liverpool-in-a-deal-worth-up-to-25m |website=[[Sky Sports]] |location=Isleworth, London, England |publisher= |access-date=18 August 2025}}</ref> A buy-back option was included in the deal for Liverpool. To reflect both his parents' names, he adopted the name "Gannon-Doak" for the back of his shirt; in place of "Doak" which he had worn in seasons prior.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11669/13414118/ben-gannon-doak-transfer-news-bournemouth-sign-winger-from-liverpool-in-a-deal-worth-up-to-25m|title=Ben Gannon Doak transfer news: Bournemouth sign winger from Liverpool in a deal worth up to £25m|work=Sky Sports News|date=19 August 2025}}</ref>

== International career ==
On 2 September 2021, after previously representing the [[Scotland national under-16 football team|under-16s]], Gannon-Doak made his debut for [[Scotland national under-17 football team|Scotland U17]], scoring in a 1–1 draw against [[Wales national under-17 football team|Wales]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scottishfa.co.uk/players/?pid=238980&lid=13|title=Ben Doak|publisher=Scottish Football Association|access-date=29 January 2022}}</ref> He helped the U17 team qualify for the [[2022 UEFA European Under-17 Championship]], but missed the tournament due to injury.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/61274162 |title=Ben Doak misses out on Scotland squad for UEFA Under-17 Championship |publisher=BBC Sport|date=29 April 2022 |access-date=29 April 2022}}</ref>

Gannon-Doak was included in the [[Scotland national under-21 football team|under-21]] squad for the first time in September 2022, aged 16.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/62837267 |title=Liverpool teenager Ben Doak one of 11 new faces in Scotland Under-21 squad |publisher=BBC Sport |date=8 September 2022 |access-date=22 September 2022}}</ref> He made his debut as a substitute on 22 September 2022 against [[Northern Ireland national under-21 football team|Northern Ireland]] and scored within seven minutes; in doing so, he became the youngest ever goalscorer for the Scotland U21s.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/62998460 |title=Under-21 international: Liverpool teenager Ben Doak scores as Scotland beat NI 3–1 in Belfast |publisher=BBC Sport |date=22 September 2022 |access-date=22 September 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/liverpool-ben-doak-scotland-goal-25086389 |title='Phenomenal talent' – Liverpool fans rave about Ben Doak as teenager scores on Scotland U21 debut |website=Liverpool Echo |date=22 September 2022 |access-date=22 September 2022}}</ref>

In May 2024, Gannon-Doak was called up to the [[Scotland national football team|senior side]] for the first time, as part of their provisional squad for [[UEFA Euro 2024]].<ref name = different>{{cite web |title=Liverpool's Doak gives 'something different' to Scots |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/c299l52x6epo |publisher=BBC Sport |access-date=22 May 2024 |date=22 May 2024}}</ref> On 4 June, he was forced to withdraw from the squad due to injury.<ref>{{cite web |title=Conway called up by Scotland as Doak drops out |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/cglljld4v0vo |publisher=BBC Sport |access-date=5 June 2024 |date=4 June 2024}}</ref>

Gannon-Doak made his senior international debut on 5 September 2024, coming on as a substitute in a 3–2 defeat to [[Poland national football team|Poland]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=English |first1=Tom |title='Scotland's capacity for self-sabotage delivers fresh horror' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/c3w605pxvewo |publisher=BBC Sport |access-date=8 September 2024 |date=5 September 2024}}</ref>

He scored his first senior international goal in a [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification – UEFA Group C|FIFA World Cup 2026 qualifier]] against [[Greece national football team|Greece]] on 15 November 2025.<ref>{{cite news |last=Canavan |first=Amy |date=15 November 2025 |title=Greece 3–2 Scotland |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/c867292849zt#Report |work=BBC Sport Scotland |location=Glasgow, Scotland |publisher=BBC |access-date=19 November 2025}}</ref> Three days later, Gannon-Doak provided an assist for a [[bicycle kick]] by [[Scott McTominay]] in the 3rd minute of a 4–2 victory against [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]], a match which sealed Scotland's first [[FIFA World Cup|World Cup]] appearance since [[1998 FIFA World Cup|1998]];<ref>{{cite news |last=Canavan |first=Amy |date=18 November 2025 |title=Scotland qualify for first men's World Cup in 28 years after Denmark epic |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/ce8glxdnx9wt |work=BBC Sport Scotland |location=Glasgow, Scotland |publisher=BBC |access-date=19 November 2025}}</ref> although he sustained an injury in the 21st minute of the match and had to be stretchered off.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Scotland 4–2 Denmark (Nov 18, 2025) Game Analysis |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/report/_/gameId/724921 |access-date=2025-11-19 |website=ESPN |language=en}}</ref>

== Personal life ==
Gannon-Doak is a practicing Christian.<ref>{{Cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=m5OklNuPmnM |title=How Ben Gannon-Doak Found Religion {{!}} A View From The Terrace |date=2026-03-08 |last=BBC Scotland |access-date=2026-03-09 |via=YouTube}}</ref>

His grandfather Martin Doak (1964–2024) was also a footballer,<ref>{{Cite web |last=Egerton |first=Nathan |date=2022-04-01 |title='Unbelievable talent', All you need to know on Liverpool bound Ben Doak |url=https://www.planetfootball.com/quick-reads/ben-doak-liverpool-target-celtic-everything-you-need-to-know-unbelievable-talent/ |access-date=2022-06-18 |website=Planet Football}}</ref> having made more than 300 appearances across two spells for [[Greenock Morton F.C.|Greenock Morton]].<ref>[https://www.fitbastats.com/morton/player.php?playerid=541 (Morton player) Doak, Martin], FitbaStats. Retrieved 3 January 2023</ref><ref>[http://www.neilbrown.newcastlefans.com/player1/martindoak.html Martin Doak], Post War English & Scottish Football League A – Z Player's Transfer Database. Retrieved 3 January 2023</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Lochrie |first1=Susan |title=Morton legend Martin Doak who is Ben Doak's grandfather dies |url=https://www.greenocktelegraph.co.uk/news/24529702.morton-legend-martin-doak-ben-doaks-grandfather-dies/ |website=[[Greenock Telegraph]] |access-date=8 September 2024 |date=20 August 2024}}</ref>

